    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "303cfff1_627e7871",
        "filename": "task_scheduler/go/scheduling/task_scheduler.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 1197,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-09-21T17:42:47Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "So we have three ways jobs are created:\n- normal commits: all jobs for the same commit get the same Created timestamp, so even if they share tasks, the task\u0027s Created timestamp should be after the jobs\u0027 timestamps.\n- forced jobs: they don\u0027t share tasks with other jobs, so the associated task timestamp should be after the job\u0027s timestamp\n- try jobs: I think this is the only way we\u0027ll hit this case: someone manually triggers a try job and then another try job later which shares a task with the first. Maybe in this case we just don\u0027t reuse the task for the second job?  We\u0027d lose some de-duplication but only when we explicitly trigger single try jobs with enough time in between so that a task has started. In cases like the commit queue this is not a concern.",
      "parentUuid": "303cfff1_7f98cf1f",
      "revId": "04c060e744893d1ae215a47f098d8cd279cc7186",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
